  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_397004810" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/397004810" />
    <a title="hawwa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11096645-hawwa"><img alt="hawwa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1437404056p2/11096645.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/397004810?book_show_action=true">Aug 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="hawwa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="hawwa" href="/user/show/11096645-hawwa">hawwa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" 9780141342702" href="/book/show/13005827-black-heart-blue">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11096645-hawwa?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer397004810" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14151421419440044280"> Twin sisters. Bound by fear. Torn apart by death.<br/><br/>Horrible. Unforgettable. Painful. This is a book that will stay with you long after you have finished reading it....<br/>Hephzibah and Rebecca are twins.<br/>Hephzibah: Born first, prettier, has always been the more popular one.<br/>Rebecca: silent, disfigured; the girl who has no confidence whatsoever and lives in her sister&apos;s shadow.<br/>Now Hephzibah has gone though, and has left Rebecca alone with the lies, secrets and abuse from her loveless parents...<br/>...and if</span>
  <span id="freeText14151421419440044280" style="display:none"> Twin sisters. Bound by fear. Torn apart by death.<br /><br />Horrible. Unforgettable. Painful. This is a book that will stay with you long after you have finished reading it....<br />Hephzibah and Rebecca are twins.<br />Hephzibah: Born first, prettier, has always been the more popular one.<br />Rebecca: silent, disfigured; the girl who has no confidence whatsoever and lives in her sister's shadow.<br />Now Hephzibah has gone though, and has left Rebecca alone with the lies, secrets and abuse from her loveless parents...<br />...and if she doesn't manage to escape from her prison-like home, she will follow the same path as her sister; who died trying..<br />First of all can I just point out the beautiful cover of this book, but also the sadness that echoes from it with the dark figure of the girl, standing before a grave. Secondly, thank you so much to Louisa Reid for sending me a copy of her début novel and signing it for me!<br />I knew this was going to be a sorrowful, shocking book but I didn't realise how much the characters would touch me, and how much this book would pull at my heart strings. At times I was so appalled I would just stop reading and stare into the distance, going over and over the words that I had just read in my mind like a film stuck on replay. The book was awash with emotions throughout; Pain. Sadness. Betrayal. Terror. Fear. Desperation. This was a seriously dark book but somehow it was so full of hope and longing, nonetheless I felt shivers creep up my spine numerous times, and desperately willed this to not be happening, not be true.**<br /><br /><br /><br />The characters were so real. Bold, beautiful Hephzibah, so alive, strong willed and desperate for freedom, and no matter how much she ignored Rebecca...she needed her more than anything. Rebecca was broken inside and also the strongest person ever. The bond between the two of them was amazing too: so real, they trusted the other with their life and this bond stretched beyond the grave. The strong descriptions of the characters helped me to step inside their shoes and witness their lives as if I was them, imprisoned and fighting for their life, but good and evil come hand in hand, there is never anything sweet and pure in the world without a dark, evil ''counter-balance''.<br />The Parents. They get a paragraph all to their sorry selves. I found it sad at the beginning that Rebecca and Hephzibah couldn't bring themselves to call their parents mum and dad, and called them The Father and The Mother...but when I heard what they had done, and were doing I was so angry...Their parents were messed up and the family was full of terror, fear, pain and violence. Hearing about what they were having up put up with every day shook me to the very core and sent shivers crawling up my spine. The father: If I could, I would attack him with my bare hands, the evil that filled this man knew no bounds and the mother was just as bad with her specialist subjects in misery and lessons of painful silence…The fact that she did nothing to stop her husband from harming her own children angered me so much....[[*insert a livid face and you'll come up with a relatively close picture to the one staring at the computer screen right now..*]]<br /><br />The one bit that kindled a bit of hope in me for Rebecca was the supporting character – Danny, and his wonderful family. They were like the ambassadors of the ''good people'' for Rebecca, supporting her and looking after her and showing both her and me that not everyone in the world is filled with hate and destruction, some people can be amazing too.<br />The book was split between Hephzi and Rebecca, switching between them every chapter. Hephzibah, bold and brave, but not so sure of herself as she'd like to be and Rebecca, timid Rebecca, but so strong and determined inside it blew my mind how lionhearted she was. The writing was beautiful! Haunting, suspenseful and simply amazing; telling us about the incredible and horrible, horrific plot. One twin told us about “Before” and the other about “After”, giving us both sides of the story. Reading about ''After'' made me desperate to know more, what had actually happened? But when I found out I wasn't so sure if I really wanted to know how everything ended up...<br />The themes in this were really, really dark. And the emotions - nonstop and overwhelming they practically drowned me. Each time something happened to one of the girls was like a punch in the gut to me. This book was worse than a horror story. Sticky, red blood spilling out of someone's neck, vampires with razor sharp teeth, I can deal with that, but this book? How many times on the news have you heard echoes of this story; girl's getting raped, young children left to die in their house, teenagers getting beaten to a pulp. Books like these are worse. They will shock you, scare you and make you feel what the girls felt as if it is real. I read this in another review and I totally agree. They're the real horror stories...<br /><br />Black Heart Blue was a book that broke my heart while making me will for everything to be Ok, hoping against hope that the outcome would pay off for the girl's efforts. With a house controlled by an abusive father with a squeaky clean outside image, and two girls, in the past and the present fighting for their lives, This book left me breathless, stunned and shaken up inside. Poignant, Powerful, just perfect.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14151421419440044280" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

